# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# Copy me:  cp .env.example .env   — then change the two secrets.
# ------------------------------------------------------------------

# Shared secret between the WhatsApp gateway and the app. CHANGE IT.
WEBHOOK_SECRET=change-me-to-a-long-random-string

# Cookie-signing secret for the dashboard. CHANGE IT.
APP_SECRET=change-me-to-another-long-random-string

# Protects the WAHA gateway API. Strongly recommended: generate one with
#   openssl rand -hex 24
# The app and the "Detect my groups" button use it automatically.
WAHA_API_KEY=

# ==================================================================
# WHATSAPP ENGINE — pick exactly ONE block below (or none — see below)
# ==================================================================
# TaskWA talks to WhatsApp through WAHA, which can run on three different
# engines. Each block sets the TWO lines WAHA needs together — WAHA_ENGINE
# and WAHA_TAG (the image) — for one engine on one CPU architecture.
# Uncomment the ONE block that matches (a) your machine's architecture and
# (b) the engine you want, and leave every other block in this section
# commented out. If you leave ALL blocks commented, you get WEBJS on
# AMD64 — TaskWA's tested default — with no action needed.
#
# Not sure of your architecture? Apple Silicon Macs (M1/M2/M3/M4) and
# Raspberry Pi are ARM64. Most cloud VPS and Intel/AMD machines are AMD64.
# Run `uname -m` in a terminal: "arm64" / "aarch64" = ARM64, "x86_64" = AMD64.
#
# Changing which block is active LATER is not a live switch — WAHA keeps a
# separate WhatsApp pairing per engine, so it needs a container rebuild AND
# a fresh QR re-pair (see the command at the end of this section, and
# TROUBLESHOOTING.md > "Switching WhatsApp engines" for the full procedure).

# ---- WEBJS on AMD64 (Intel/AMD servers, most cloud VPS) ----------
# Headless Chromium. The most mature and best-documented engine, and the
# one TaskWA is built and tested against — the safe default. Heaviest on
# RAM (roughly 400-600MB) — fine on a VPS with 2GB+, can be tight on a
# small or shared box.
# WAHA_ENGINE=WEBJS
# WAHA_TAG=

# ---- WEBJS on ARM64 (Apple Silicon Mac, Raspberry Pi) ------------
# Same engine as above, ARM build.
# WAHA_ENGINE=WEBJS
# WAHA_TAG=arm

# ---- NOWEB on AMD64 -----------------------------------------------
# No browser — a much lighter WebSocket client (Baileys). Uses far less
# RAM than WEBJS, which is the appeal on a small host. Trade-off: it needs
# WAHA's "Store" enabled for contacts/group lookups, and has open
# compatibility gaps around @lid (privacy-hidden participant) resolution.
# Read taskwa-noweb-evaluation.md before pointing a production system at
# this — it's directionally promising, not a drop-in swap.
# WAHA_ENGINE=NOWEB
# WAHA_TAG=noweb

# ---- NOWEB on ARM64 -------------------------------------------------
# Same engine and trade-offs as above, ARM build.
# WAHA_ENGINE=NOWEB
# WAHA_TAG=noweb-arm

# ---- GOWS on AMD64 --------------------------------------------------
# No browser — a newer Go-based client (whatsmeow), also light on RAM.
# The WAHA maintainer's recommended alternative to NOWEB, but younger and
# not yet tested against TaskWA specifically. Check WAHA's current
# licensing for this engine before committing to it in production —
# https://waha.devlike.pro/docs — engine availability has shifted between
# free and paid tiers before.
# WAHA_ENGINE=GOWS
# WAHA_TAG=gows

# ---- GOWS on ARM64 --------------------------------------------------
# Same engine and caveats as above, ARM build.
# WAHA_ENGINE=GOWS
# WAHA_TAG=gows-arm

# ---- After changing the block above, apply it with: -----------------
#   docker compose up -d --force-recreate waha
# This restarts ONLY the gateway container — tasks, history, and the app
# itself are untouched. If you only changed architecture for the SAME
# engine (e.g. moved WEBJS from a VPS to a Mac), the existing pairing
# should survive. If you changed the ENGINE itself, expect a fresh QR —
# each engine keeps its own separate session — so re-pair from the
# dashboard Health page once the container is back up.

# ---- optional: e-mail alerts when the WhatsApp session drops ------
SMTP_HOST=
SMTP_PORT=587
SMTP_USER=
SMTP_PASSWORD=
SMTP_FROM=
ALERT_EMAIL=

# ---- optional: healthchecks.io heartbeat URL ----------------------
HEALTHCHECKS_URL=
